post_text:
United ISD Elementary Schools Kick-Off Accelerated Reader Program

United ISD’s Elementary schools virtually kicked off the start of the 2020-2021 Accelerated Reader (AR) program with a reading-themed virtual celebration. Every year, elementary campuses participate in the AR program, which is geared at motivating students to read more. The students accumulate points based on the books they read and each school has the opportunity to reward their students for reaching their point goals. Students participated in various virtual activities such as dressing as their favorite book characters, making sock puppets, and wearing t-shirts depicting book characters.

post_text:
Retired Fire Cheif Steve Landin Addresses Students AT LBJ in Honor of Patriot Day

Former City of Laredo Fire Chief and current Webb County Emergency Management Coordinator Steve E. Landin virtually addressed students at Lyndon B. Johnson High School in honor of Patriot Day. Landin discussed the emotions and fears that enveloped Americans on September 11, 2001, and the operational changes that were made in response to the events. Landin spoke of the heroism and selflessness shown by the first responders of New York City and surrounding areas.

Landin further communicated the intense pressure that first responders are repeatedly placed under. Mr. Landin took questions from the students and detailed some of his experiences throughout his career.

Requisitos para los estudiantes de pre-kinder, deben de tener 4 años cumplidos para el 1 de Septiembre del 2020.

Los documentos que se necesitan para la inscripción:

ESTUDIANTE:
• Acta de nacimiento original o copia certificada
• Tarjeta del Seguro Social
• Boleta de calificaciones de la escuela anterior (de ser pertinente)
• Cartilla de vacunación actualizada, incluyendo examen de tuberculosis

PADRES/TUTORES:
• Licencia de conducir o tarjeta de identificación emitida por el estado (con dirección de su residencia actual)
• Prueba de residencia (recibo de luz, agua o gas del mes actual o el anterior
• Dirección de correo electrónico vigente/activa

Seleccione el siguiente enlace para mas información.

https://tea.texas.gov/academics/early-childhood-education/general-prekindergarten-faq

post_text:
Requirements for Pre-Kindergarten: student/child must be 4 years old on or before September 1, 2020

To Register your child you will need the following:
STUDENT:
• An original or certified copy of the child's birth certificate
• Child's Social Security card
• Reportcard from previous school (if applicable)
• An up-to-date immunization records, including a TB test

PARENT/GUARDIAN:
• Driver license or state-issued identification card (address must reflect current residence)
• Proof of residency (current or prior month's electric bill, water bill, gas bill
• A current/active email address

In addition to the age requirement, the student must qualify for the Pre-K program. Click the link below for requirements.

https://tea.texas.gov/academics/early-childhood-education/general-prekindergarten-faq

United Independent School District added 3 new photos.
September 2 at 8:46 PM ·

The Webb County’s Emergency Assistance Team (E.A.T.), in collaboration with The Gonzalez-Fischer Family and United ISD, donated boxes of chicken breasts to families in need throughout the City of Laredo. The donation amounted to nearly 5,000 pounds of chicken and over 100 families received an entire box of chicken breasts.

“Helping one family at a time is our mission, our statement, and our goal,” stated Cristobal Rodriguez, III, Founder of E.A.T. The Emergency Assistance Team is a Texas non-profit organization formed to give assistance to families within Webb County and surrounding areas in times of need. Founders of E.A.T. include; Cristobal Rodriguez, III, Jessica Palacios, Selma Canche, Edgar O. Gonzalez, and Arturo Sanchez.

post_text:
Orangetheory Fitness of Laredo Donates School Supplies to UISD Students

Recently, two representatives from Laredo's Orangetherory Fitness donated a variety of school supplies for distribution to UISD students who need a little extra help. The donation included a variety of markers, notebooks, crayon markers, pencils, pens, theme paper, and glue sticks. "Orangetheory Fitness enjoys the opportunity to help our students in any way we can. We hope that these supplies will help them get a good start to the school year", said General Manager Illan Arguindegui.

UISD Thanks Orangetheory Fitness!

Photographed with a portion of the donated school supplies are:

Front, L-R: UISD Senior Auditor Laura Garcia and Orangetheory Regional Fitness Director, Ally Martinez

Back L-R: Orangetheory Laredo General Manager Illan Arguindegui and UISD Deputy Supt. for Administration and Operations Gloria Rendon

post_text:
City of Laredo Environmental Services Donates Tote Bags to Kazen Elementary Students

As is the case for thousands of students in our community, the current pandemic has made it necessary for Kazen elementary students to receive classroom instruction at home. To make things easier, John Porter and Blasita Lopez from the City of Laredo Environmental Services Department donated reusable bags during a drive-by distribution at the campus on August 12 and 13. The students utilized the bags to carry home their Chromebooks or Ipads along with school books and assignment packets. "I wish to thank Mr. Porter, Ms. Lopez, and the City of Laredo Environmental Services for their generous donation to our students", said Monica Arriaga, Principal. City of Laredo Environmental Services Donates Tote Bags to Kazen Elementary Students.

Pictured: L-R: Kazen Elem. first-grade student Andria Garza and fifth-grade student Alessandra Garza
with their tote bags - courtesy of the City of Laredo Environmental Services!

Call Center Available to Assist Parents of United ISD

United ISD has created a call center in order to alleviate any questions or concerns parents may have regarding virtual learning and any other issues that may arise. The call center’s phone number 956-473-8000. Lines will be open Monday through Friday from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. Parents may call this number for assistance with logging into Google Classroom, password resets, questions about Grab and Go meals, or for any other questions, they may have.

August 14 at 9:39 PM ·

United ISD's Office of Professional Development welcomed the district’s 85 new teachers with a drive-thru "grab and go lunch" at United ISD's Curriculum and Instruction (C&I), building located on Hwy.359. Associate Superintendent David H.Gonzalez and staff cheered the new teachers as they arrived to pick up a complimentary Chick-fil-A lunch and teaching supplies starter kit. "We are very excited with the quality teachers we have added to our already wonderful staff. We also look forward to all the great things our new teachers will contribute to the district, and wish them a successful 2020-2021 school year" Gonzalez said.

shared_text:
United Independent School District added 2 new photos — at United Independent School District.
August 10 at 6:31 PM ·

United ISD’s New Teacher Orientation Sessions began on Monday, August 10 and will continue through Thursday, August 13. The sessions are being held online, and mark the commencement of the teacher induction process for newly certified teachers and teachers new to the district. The purpose of the sessions is to introduce teachers to the school district’s mission, goals, expectations and procedures. The sessions began with a welcome message from Superintendent Roberto J. Santos.

“We are pleased to welcome our new teachers to the United ISD family. Our District is moving forward with remote learning, and our administrators, principals, and teachers are committed to providing consistent and rigorous instruction on a daily basis. We are also focusing on the emotional well-being of our students as they adjust to receiving their academic instruction at home", said United ISD’s Deputy Superintendent for Administration and Operations Gloria Rendon. The first day of remote learning (for all United ISD campuses), is Monday, August 24.

post_text:
United ISD Transportation Department Assists Webb County Sheriff’s Office SWAT Team with School Bus for Training

Recently, United ISD provided a school bus to the Webb County Sheriff’s Office to assist with a hostage crisis training for their SWAT Team. Members of the SWAT Team utilized a United ISD school bus to run through the breach and clear training. Members of the SWAT Team donned their full tactical gear during the crisis training while their commanding officer went through the procedure of negotiation. Mr. Joe Aranda, the Executive Director of United ISD’s Transportation Department, stated, “The District is always willing to help law enforcement with trainings like these. They keep our students and our community safe and we are very thankful for their service.”

La Transferencia Electrónica de Beneficios por Pandemia (P-EBT, por sus siglas en inglés) es un beneficio de alimentos único para las familias que perdieron el acceso a comidas gratuitas o a precio reducido debido al cierre de las escuelas. A fin de mayo, las escuelas les enviarán instrucciones para realizar una solicitud a las familias elegibles para la P-EBT. La solicitud de la P-EBT estará disponible la primera semana de junio.

Los beneficios de alimentos de la P-EBT son para los niños que recibieron beneficios de alimentos del Programa Asistencial de Nutrición Suplementaria (SNAP, por sus siglas en inglés) para marzo de 2020 y para los niños que estén certificados para recibir comidas gratuitas o a precio reducido en Texas durante el año escolar 2019-20. Para obtener más información, visite: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

📷

post_text:
Borchers Elementary Bids Farewell to Their Graduating 5th Graders

Recently, Borchers Elementary held a drive-thru parade at their campus to bid farewell to their 5th-grade students who are moving on to middle school. Parents and students decorated their vehicles in the school’s colors and dressed festively while honking their horns in celebration. Students were greeted by their 5th-grade teachers who gave them their awards for the year and treated them to a Chick-Fil-A boxed lunch. Students were thrilled to see their teachers one last time before moving on to middle school.

post_text:
Nye Elementary School Farewell Parade Cheers on Students!

Recently, Nye elementary school teachers, staff, and special population educators collaborated with parents to organize an end-of-school year parade at the campus on Friday, May 22. Approximately 80 Nye elementary families partook of the festivities by cruising through the campus parking lot. Most of the automobiles were decorated with balloons, posters and messages expressing support and encouragement. Several Nye elementary teachers waved and held signs that celebrated the student’s accomplishments and wished them a happy and safe summer break.

"We are going to miss our students, and we want them to know that we are here to help them in any way that we can", said Principal Cynthia Caballero. "I also wish to thank our parents and teachers for making this event memorable for our 5th grade Wildcats who will begin middle school in the fall. We wish them the very best in the next chapter of their education", she concluded.

post_text: Good morning as this school year slowly comes to an end. I want to thank UISD for all the hard work everyone has done during this pandemic. I want to give a special thanks to our 3rd grade teacher Mrs. Perez De Llanos from Borchers Elementary. She has been a sweetheart to her class. Seeing the faces of her kids during virtual meetings was the best. Without knowing this pandemic made us realize and value all the great work teachers do. Mrs. Perez has made everything so easy for all her students. She did not only have to help her students she also had to teach us “parents”. She was always answering questions for us. Also, a special thanks to Ms. Lerma our PE coach she made these weeks so fun for our kids, I even participated on the physical activities with our son. Thank you, our counselor Ms. Beltran. All the material she sent would not only help the students, but I also help us as parents during these times of anxiety. Thank you from the bottom of my heart. God bless everyone.

Officers driving their patrol cars arrived at the main entrance of the school to the curbside celebration in their honor. NJHS members and school administrators brought food to their units and at the same time said ‘thank you’ for their service to UISD’s students and schools.

Joining the celebration were Ramiro Veliz III, Board of Trustees President; Ricardo "Rick" Rodriguez, Board Secretary; Jessica Salazar, LOMS Principal; Brenda Cognata, NJHS Sponsor; Captain Aaron Salazar; National Junior Honor Society members; and United ISD Police Department officers.

United Independent School District added 8 new photos.
May 8 at 4:30 AM ·

Today our Athletics Department department handed out almost 200 meals to our UISD Athletics coaches for teacher appreciation week.

Coach Cruz said he was reminded of a couple of things today:
1. These fine hard working coaches are ESSENTIAL to our department and to our students.
2. I miss working alongside them and watching their teams compete and succeed.
3. I miss my amazing office staff of coordinators and assistants and I'm lucky to be surrounded by smart and fun people who put up with me.
4. If you offer food, everyone shows up! 😂
5. Our coaches and staff can't wait to get back to teaching face to face & coaching up our kids. AND
6. It was great to see everyone just healthy and happy to see each other.
Big thanks to Patrick Michael Santos at Pat's Kitchen and his wife for feeding our coaches today! Our coaches and staff appreciated it more than you know. Plus, we got to help a local small business today. WIn win! UISD PROUD! @uisdathletics beyond the X's and O's.

United Independent School District added 4 new photos — in Laredo, Texas.
April 30 at 9:32 PM · Laredo, TX ·

This morning, Ramiro Veliz, III, United ISD’s Board President, distributed free face masks to parents during the Grab and Go meal distribution site at Los Obispos Middle School.
During the giveaway, Veliz thanked all the parents for their patience and cooperation during this pandemic.

Mr. Veliz also recognized and thanked the cafeteria staff for all their hard work. The Child Nutrition Department distributes between 16 to 18 thousand meals a day.

Participating in passing out face masks were UISD Police Captain Aaron Salazar, Sgt. Sergio Garcia and Police Officer Iram Vicharelli.

Beginning Monday, May 4, 2020, United ISD is adding nine additional Grab and Go Food sites, for a total of 27 free meal sites. The sites will be open Monday-Friday, from 10 a.m. to 11:30 a.m. For a list of all locations, please visit the district website at www.uisd.net

United ISD Board Member Ricardo "Rick" Rodriguez paid a visit to the Grab and Go free meal distribution sites at Bonnie Garcia Elementary School and Antonio Gonzalez Middle School. Rodriguez accompanied the United ISD Cafeteria Staff and Police Administrators to distribute face masks to the families in the car-line, expressing his support during these difficult times.

Beginning Monday, May 4, 2020, United ISD is adding nine additional Grab and Go Food sites making it a total of 27 free meal sites. The sites will be open Monday-Friday, from 10 a.m. to 11:30 a.m. For a list of all locations, please visit the district website at www.uisd.net.

United ISD Board Member Ricardo "Rick" Rodriguez paid a visit to the Grab and Go free meal distribution sites at Bonnie Garcia Elementary School and Antonio Gonzalez Middle School. Rodriguez accompanied the United ISD Cafeteria Staff and Police Administrators to distribute face masks to the families in the car-line, expressing his support during these difficult times.

Beginning Monday, May 4, 2020, United ISD is adding nine additional Grab and Go Food sites making it a total of 27 free meal sites. The sites will be open Monday-Friday, from 10 a.m. to 11:30 a.m. For a list of all locations, please visit the district website at www.uisd.net.

United Independent School District added 9 new photos.
March 5 at 10:18 PM ·

The 2020 Special Olympics Texas Area 21 Spring Games kicked off at UISD’s SAC on March 2. Approximately 900 athletes from UISD, LISD, and area school districts participated in the opening ceremonies. The event started with the traditional promenade of special athletes accompanied by their principals, teachers and fellow students. The presentation of colors was executed by the Alexander High School JROTC under the direction of SFC Joseph Garcia. The National Anthem was performed by the Alexander High School band under the direction of Josh Martinez.

Following a one lap run of the Olympic torch by local, district and area law enforcement volunteers, UISD Superintendent Roberto J. Santos and LISD Assistant Superintendent Gerardo Cruz lit the official Olympic flame with UISD’s High School Athletes of the Year Mary Fernanda Guerra from Alexander High School and Gilberto Perez from UISD Cherish Center.

Special thanks to all UISD employees and students who assisted and the athletes!

UISD Student Earns Top Spot in State-Wide Video Contest

Trautmann Middle School student Alondra Paez brought pride to her family and campus with her 1st place ranking in the 6th-8th-grade division of the annual Taking Care of Texas (TCOT), Video Contest. The contest had almost 600 middle and high school students submit their video projects for consideration. This year’s challenge was to produce a video that would help fellow Texans learn what they can do to protect our environment. Ms. Paez’s first-place prize is a Go-Pro Premium package. “Alondra put a lot of work and creativity into her project. I would also like to congratulate her cast members for a job well done”, said Principal Leticia Menchaca.

Ms. Paez' winning entry can be seen at http://takecareoftexas.org/teens/video-contest/video-contest-winners

Ms. Paez’s first-place prize is a Go-Pro Premium package. “Alondra put a lot of work and creativity into her project. I would also like to congratulate her cast members for a job well done”, said Principal Leticia Menchaca.

Ms. Paez' winning entry can be seen at http://takecareoftexas.org/teens/video-contest/video-contest-winners

Recently, 50 Antonio Gonzalez Middle School 8th graders in the GEAR UP program participated in the STEM Camp, an all-day on-campus robotics camp. Reybotics is a robotics company founded by Heriberto Reynoso in the Rio Grande Valley. Part of the company's mission is to educate the younger generation about Science, Technology, Engineering, and Math (STEM) careers through interactive lesson plans. During the Reybotics STEM camp, the students learned about the growing STEM fields, future careers, and participated in four different activities. The students participated in launching water-powered rockets, learning about and flying aerial drones and got to fly drones through an obstacle course, manipulated circuit boards and learned about their functions, and also practiced building a hexabot, a six-legged robot.

Reybotics Aerospace and Discovery camps were held at Raul Perales Middle School under the auspices of the Region One ESC Gear Up initiative. The camps promote the importance of higher education and college readiness by increasing students awareness of career opportunities in fields of science and engineering. The camps conveyed learning concepts in rocketry, drones, gravitational physics, circuits, hexapods and coding. Following some classroom instruction, the students were given an opportunity to apply their knowledge using “Mission to Mars” robots and drones. Reybotics founder Heriberto Reynoso structured his curriculum to inspire students to take an early interest in STEM related fields. “It is essential that we give students an opportunity to discover the incredible opportunities that await them in science and technology related fields", said Heriberto Reynoso, CEO/Founder of Reybotics.

Sons and Daughters of Liberty Visit San Isidro Elementary School!

In keeping with a community tradition, students at four UISD elementary schools are enjoying visits from the WBCA's "Sons and Daughters of Liberty". The Society of Martha Washington takes great pride in offering students a unique opportunity to experience a living history lesson. The group is comprised of volunteers who portray historical figures of the revolutionary and colonial periods. This year's first stop was at San Isidro Elementary School.

Pictured: Front Row, L-R: Jennie Reed as Mistress Sally Smythe; Chris Notzon as Benjamin Tallmadge; Norma Moore as Margaret Corbin; Elizabeth Rubio and Joe Rubio, this year's Martha and George Washington; Anna Isabel Alvarez as Deborah Sampson; Rocky Bruni as Patrick Henry, and
Violeta Zertuche as Betsy Ross.

February 6 at 4:36 PM ·

February 5th was World Read Aloud Day in our country. This day celebrates the importance of sharing stories in the literacy community. Aside from the joy that stories bring, there are many benefits in sharing a read aloud; so this day is now being observed by 173 countries and counting. Freedom Elementary honored this day, teachers chose a special reader to read a story to a neighboring class. Before the student began their read aloud, they were surprised by a letter from their homeroom teacher. This letter expressed the honor that the teacher felt in having such a great reader and thanked them for sharing their gift of reading to another class. The students were both excited and a little nervous at the beginning of the day. However at the end of the day the readers' smiles and attitude expressed the honor and pleasure of having been selected to read to others. It was a simple celebration but one that will be cemented in the memories of many students.

Former United South Baseball Pitcher and Panther Legend Roel Ramirez was inducted into the United ISD League of Legends Program in 2019. Unfortunately, he was unable to attend the induction ceremonies due to his baseball schedule. He paid a special visit to Panther Land on Wednesday, February 5, 2020. He was honored in a ceremony at the school's library, where he spoke to JV and Varsity Baseball and Softball teams about his experience at USHS and his successful baseball career. Ramirez is now in 3AAA baseball in the St. Louis Cardinals organization and is reporting later this week to the Cardinals Spring Training complex in West Palm Beach Florida and reporting with the Major League Team for the Cardinals. Pitchers and catchers report first to the major leagues to start spring training for the first few weeks of spring training. Then followed by the rest of the position players. After several weeks Ramirez will know if he will stay in the bigs with the Cardinals or reassigned to a Triple AAA team.

United ISD and the Fine Arts Department are proud to host the annual Region XIV 9th Grade Clinic and Concert on Friday, January 31, 2020.

The concert will be held at UISD's Bill Johnson Student Activity Complex Auditorium and begins at 6:00 PM.

Admission charge is $3.00 for Adults, and $1.00 for school-age students (with school ID).

This concert will feature 9th-grade band members from LISD, UISD, Gregory Portland and Flour Bluff HS. These students qualified for this band through an audition process that required them to perform 3 prepared musical etudes for a panel of judges.

Students will rehearse on Thursday afternoon and Friday at the SAC Auditorium to prepare for the concert.

Juan G. Sosa, JW Nixon HS Band Director is the TMEA Region XIV 9th Grade Region Chair.

The public is invited to attend.

For more information contact the UISD Fine Arts Department at (956) 473-7121.

United ISD and the Fine Arts Department are proud to host the annual Middle School Region Band Clinic and Concert on Saturday, January 25, 2020.

The concert will be held at UISD's Bill Johnson Student Activity Complex Auditorium and begins at 4:00 PM.
Admission charge is $3.00 for Adults and $1.00 for school-age students. The public is invited to attend.

This concert will feature 3 Region Bands, Concert Band (82 members), Symphonic Band (82 members) and the Honors Band (65 members).

Conductors for the bands are:
Yolanda Moreno, (Laredo) Concert Band, Ken Peach, (Boerne ISD) Symphonic Band and Jessica Gonzalez, (Four Points MS, Leander) Honors Band

All 3 bands combined have a grand total of 229 students from Laredo ISD and United ISD who qualified for the region bands by performing 3 musical excerpts for a panel of judges.
Those students receiving the most points qualified to be a Region Band member for Music Region XIV.

For more information contact the UISD Fine Arts Department at (95) 473-7121

United South H.S. Team Captains Give Sheriff Martin Cuellar A Special Gift!

Recently, Coach Joe Coss and captains from the United South HS Varsity Football Team visited Webb County Sheriff headquarters to present Sheriff Martin Cuellar with a football helmet signed by all of the players. Coach Coss said that the helmet was a token of appreciation for Cuellar’s commitment to our community, school safety, and sports. “We want our students to be good citizens. Football gives them a platform to work together as a team, and their united effort yields positive results. When it comes to working as a team, Sheriff Cuellar and his officers and are excellent role models” said Coss.

Photo: United South HS – Varsity football coach, Jose Coss; captains: Efrain Hernandez, William Noble, Jonathan Herandez, Mark Trujillo, and Sheriff Martin Cuellar

Region One Christmas Card Competition Winner at UMS

United Middle School (UMS) is proud to announce the winner of this year's Region 1 Christmas Card competition. The winner, UMS student Natalie Gonzalez, competed against hundreds of other young artists across the region. Her artwork depicted a unique and original scene where we can admire Mr. and Mrs. Claus dancing to the sounds of the Mexican culture, which represent her community and the traditions we hold dear on the border. As part of her award, Gonzalez's card will be distributed to all campuses across the region as the Holiday Card of the year at the Middle School level. For more information, please visit Region One.

post_text:
Centeno Elementary Holds Grand Opening of Centenoville



Centeno Elementary recently celebrated the grand opening of Centenoville, a minitropolis within the school’s walls. For the 5th years now, Commerce Bank has sponsored the mini-city designed to teach the students how to manage real-world issues, all the while teaching them financial responsibility. Students can work as bank president or vice-president, tellers, store vendors, security guards and various other jobs designed to mimic the real world. Centenoville’s minitropolis offers a variety of organizations geared towards teaching students fiscal responsibility. These organizations include Commerce Bank, Centenoville mart, a radio station, its own Border Patrol sector, and a police station. United ISD and Centeno Elementary principal, Ms. Amabilia Gonzalez, wish to thank Commerce Bank President Ignacio Urrabazo, Jr., and Commerce Bank for their continuous dedication and support of the Centenoville Program.

post_text: Roberto "Bobby" Quintana, Justice of the Peace Pct. 2, Pl. 1 was the special guest host for this year's first middle school Knowledge for College academic show. Salvador Garcia Middle School students Mario Hernandez and Kimberly Vasquez represented their school, while students Ramiro Tijerina and Justin Bernal represented United South Middle School. Instructional Television Department Communications Specialist, Jose Sanchez, hosted the program with Judge Quintana. Proud parents were also in the studio audience, along with J.P. Court Coordinator Mary Serna. Judge Quintana was very impressed with the students' knowledge in the areas of Math, Science, Social Studies, and Language Arts. The program will air weekend mornings during the holidays on a few local stations. We'll be posting the television schedule soon, so stay tuned!

post_text:
UISD Parents Attend December 2019 U.C.O.P. Meeting

UISD Federal Programs recently hosted the final United Council of Parents (U.C.O.P.), meeting for 2019 at the District's Student Activity Complex. The agenda included discussions about mental health awareness, intervention, suicide prevention, availability of community services to help students, and a threat assessment presentation. U.C.O.P. meetings are held during the school year, and topics of discussion are designed to increase parental involvement with children at home and at school. The District offers UISD parents complimentary transportation to the meetings upon request. For inquiries about the next U.C.O.P. meeting and related transportation services, please call 473-6259.

Pictured: Ms. Gloria Rendon, UISD Deputy Superintendent for Administration & Operations was one of many presenters at the December 2019 UCOP meeting. Ms. Rendon discussed threat assessments as they relate to campus and district safety protocols.

post_text:
Reading on the Roof at U.M.S.

At United Middle School, a culture of reading gets rewarded. Every six weeks, the school hosts an event for students that have met their reading goal for those six weeks. This occasion, the school hosted the "Reading on the Roof" event where students from 6th through 8th grade that met their goal attended and enjoyed the reading of "Diary of a Wimpy Kid 'The Melt Down'" with Mr. Carlos Ramirez leading the lecture. The activity invites students to read along with their copy of the book, which they also got to keep. Students were also encouraged to read out loud to their classmates.
